Prosper Loan Explanatory analysis¶

Effectiveness of Prosper score as compared to other variables¶

In this analysis, we will look at the effectiveness of prosper score as an instrument to identify risk of borrowers and how it stacks up against other variables

Borrower Rate vs Debt to Income ratio

This was expected to have strong positive correlation. Higher the debt to income higher will be the borrower rate. But understandably borrower rate hits a ceiling around 0.31 to 0.35 mark weakening the correlation coefficient. Of course you cannot keep increasing borrower rate forever, which will make your platform unattractive for users with high debt. Believe adding Credit_Rating will throw more light into this hypothesis.

To show the difference in loan performance among the income groups we have to write a function which provides % split within the income group among various hues with help from a stackoverflow.com thread.

In [20]:
def with_hue(data,x,hue_y,title,xtitle): 
    df1 = data.groupby(x)[hue_y].value_counts(normalize=True)
    df1 = df1.mul(100)
    df1 = df1.rename('Percent').reset_index()
    g = sb.catplot(x=x,y='Percent',hue=hue_y,kind='bar',data=df1,)
    g.ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    g.ax.set_title(title)
    g.ax.set_xlabel(xtitle)    
    for p in g.ax.patches:
        txt = str(p.get_height().round().astype(int)) + '%'
        txt_x = p.get_x() 
        txt_y = p.get_height()
        g.ax.text(txt_x,txt_y,txt)

Did prosper score get it right when it comes to estimated return ? Hue on credit rating

Separating into good loan and bad loan, we notice that both looks similar in pattern except few points that stands out in the lower & middle scores.
1) There seems to be many HR rated good loans which were assigned lower prosper score (0 to 4), in lower income groups (< 7500 monthly income)
2) There is a good amount of AA rated good loans when compared to bad loans in the scores between 6 & 8
One inference is clear, Prosper scores aren't perfect as very few things are in the world with room to improve

Key Takeways¶

Points to note

1) Income is definitely not a key factor to identify good borrowers from bad borrowers
2) The group with high risk and return seems to be Employed + Full time group with relatively lower credit rating of D & E with good loans return between 0.1 and 0.2
3) Risk is built in when assigning borrower rate which correlates strongly with estimated return

Key misses with prosper score as a risk identification factor

1) Number Defaults is almost equal on either side of prosper score of 6
2) High score for high income groups with lower credit rating
3) High scores for groups with high debt to income ratio

Key factors to identify borrower riks within analysis scope

1) Credit Rating
2) Debt to Income Ratio, which may have accounted for in credit rating
3) Prosper score
